From 55caa1c8e16f4a6036d164c6c4c82ad3a155dccc Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: dfattal <dfattal@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 14 Jul 2026 22:55:59 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 39/41] inline-3d(#625): keep rendering while the page is
 visible but unfocused
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Clicking away from the browser made the 3D windows smear in place — the same
stale-sub-rect corruption as the startup case, with a different trigger.

UpdateVisibilityState forces an inline session to HIDDEN whenever the frame
loses focus, and MaybeRequestFrame refuses frames while HIDDEN. For an ordinary
inline session that is exactly right: no focus, no poses to script. But an
inline-3d session's output is not a pose handed to script, it is PIXELS ON THE
PANEL. Its frames drive the app's canvas repaints, and the compositor weaves
whatever those canvases last held — so stopping them drops the canvas layers out
of the aggregated frame and the weave starts reading stale sub-rects. The user
sees content they are still looking at visibly corrupt, because they clicked
another window. Visible-but-unfocused is the normal state of a 3D display
sitting alongside other apps.

So exempt inline-3d from the focus gate; document visibility still governs.

The exposure this opens is narrower than it looks: an unfocused inline-3d page
keeps receiving eye-derived views, but it is on-screen and already having its
content woven from those same eyes, and a genuinely hidden page stops regardless
— inline frames ride the document's rAF, which Blink throttles for background
tabs.
---
 .../blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc     | 17 ++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 16 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc b/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc
index 069d36dfe271d..35c0b29efce4c 100644
--- a/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc
+++ b/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc
@@ -1754,7 +1754,22 @@ void XRSession::UpdateVisibilityState() {
   // because while the runtime reports us as focused the content owned by the
   // session should be focued, which is owned by the document. For inline, we
   // can and must rely on frame focus.
-  if (!immersive() && !xr_->IsFrameFocused()) {
+  //
+  // ...except for inline-3d (#625), where the session's output is not a pose
+  // handed to script but PIXELS ON THE GLASSES-FREE-3D PANEL. Its frames drive
+  // the app's canvas repaints, and the compositor weaves whatever those
+  // canvases last held: stop the frames and the canvas layers fall out of the
+  // aggregated frame, so the weave reads stale sub-rects and the page's 3D
+  // windows visibly smear. Merely clicking another window would corrupt content
+  // the user is still looking at. Visible-but-unfocused is the normal state of
+  // a 3D display alongside other apps, so keep rendering.
+  //
+  // This does mean an unfocused inline-3d page keeps receiving eye-derived
+  // views. That is a narrower exposure than it looks: the page is on-screen and
+  // already having its content woven from those same eyes, and a genuinely
+  // hidden page stops anyway — inline frames ride the document's rAF, which
+  // Blink throttles for background tabs.
+  if (!immersive() && !is_inline_3d_ && !xr_->IsFrameFocused()) {
     state = XRVisibilityState::HIDDEN;
   }
 
